# Fluff Date: 2026-02-21 18:07:19
overview:<p>The White Flame is a 70-ton heavy quad BattleMech introduced in 3065 by the Word of Blake. Produced at the Mitchell Vehicles factory on Terra, the design emerged alongside its sister chassis, the Blue Flame, as part of a concerted Blakist effort to field quad combat 'Mechs. The White Flame was intended primarily for guerrilla operations, leveraging its speed and jump capability to strike fast and withdraw before enemies could concentrate fire.</p><p>Like many Word of Blake 'Mechs, the majority of production was funneled to shadow divisions and militia units rather than openly deployed formations. The design earned a fearsome reputation during the Jihad for its effectiveness in ambush and raiding operations, though the fall of Terra in 3078 effectively ended its production run.</p>

capabilities:<p>The White Flame is fast and mobile for a heavy 'Mech, capable of reaching 86 kph on the ground and clearing 150 meters in a single jump. Its five Rawlings 60 jump jets, installed in each of the quad's four legs and the center torso, produce a spectacular visual effect when firing, making the 'Mech appear to ignite from below as it leaps. The quad configuration provides exceptional stability on landing, with the four legs flexing to absorb impact while the center torso jet cushions the descent.</p><p>Offensively, the WHF-3B carries an all-energy weapons loadout centered on a Tronel XIII large pulse laser and a Tronel XII medium pulse laser, supplemented by a pair of Diverse Optics extended-range medium lasers. This configuration eliminates ammunition dependency, allowing extended independent operations far from supply lines. A McArthur anti-missile system provides point defense, while a Dornman Echo II communications system with integrated C3i computer enables the White Flame to share targeting data across a networked lance.</p><p>Fifteen tons of StarSlab armor give the White Flame respectable protection, though its damage output is modest compared to other heavy 'Mechs. The design philosophy favors hit-and-run tactics over sustained engagement, relying on speed and coordination rather than raw firepower. Stand-up slugfests will leave the heavy quad rapidly defeated despite its armor and anti-missile defenses, as the quad configuration limits the 'Mech's ability to protect its rear arc.</p>

deployment:<p>Introduced in 3069 during the Jihad, this variant replaced the pulse laser armament with a Ceres Arms Crusher plasma rifle, dramatically increasing the variant's threat profile. The plasma rifle's ability to raise target heat levels proved devastating against opposing 'Mechs, particularly those already running hot from sustained combat. To accommodate the heavier weapon, designers sacrificed a ton of armor and one double heat sink, while adding a heavy-duty gyro to improve survivability under fire. The extended-range medium lasers, C3i computer, and anti-missile system were retained, though AMS ammunition was halved. The shorter optimal range of the plasma rifle encouraged more aggressive tactics, with pilots closing rapidly to maximize the weapon's heat-inducing effects.</p>

history:<p>The White Flame's origins are rooted in the Word of Blake's ambition to develop a new generation of quad BattleMechs during the early 3060s. When the Blakists reopened the Mitchell Vehicles factory on Terra, they dedicated a production section specifically to quad designs. Two chassis were planned from the outset, the Blue Flame and the White Flame, but development stalled when engineers could not reconcile the desired weapons loadouts with the space constraints inherent in quad 'Mech design. The acquisition of Lyran light engine technology through ROM espionage during the FedCom Civil War resolved the impasse, and the WHF-3B entered production in 3065.</p><p>Distribution of the White Flame followed the Word of Blake's characteristic pattern of secrecy. While production numbers were respectable, the 'Mechs that reached militia units represented only a fraction of total output. Intelligence analysts debated whether the remainder were being modified after production for specialized roles or held in reserve by one of the Word's shadow divisions. The truth remained elusive throughout the Jihad, as Blakist operational security made accurate force assessments nearly impossible.</p><p>The White Flame saw its most extensive combat deployment during the Jihad, where both the base WHF-3B and the plasma-armed WHF-3C proved effective in the guerrilla and raiding operations that characterized much of the Word's defensive strategy. Reports from multiple fronts described White Flames using their jump capability to ambush enemy lances from concealed positions, delivering punishing strikes before withdrawing. The quad's stability made it particularly effective at firing while airborne, and the C3i network integration multiplied the threat when White Flames operated in coordinated groups.</p><p>The fall of Terra in 3078 effectively ended White Flame production. The Mitchell Vehicles facility passed to Republic of the Sphere control, but the factory's White Flame line was not reactivated. Surviving examples scattered across former Blakist holdings became increasingly rare battlefield prizes, valued for their unusual combination of heavy 'Mech durability and light 'Mech mobility. The design's reliance on Word of Blake-specific technology, particularly the C3i computer systems, complicated maintenance for non-Blakist operators, further reducing the number of operational White Flames as the post-Jihad era progressed.</p>

